I apologize for the confusion. Since you are using Stripe redirect to Checkout, you don't have control over the design and template of the checkout page. However, what you can do is modify the line item description before passing it to Stripe.

Assuming you have a JavaScript object holding the line item data, you can update it like so:

```javascript
let nights = 10;
let pricePerNight = 50;

let lineItem = {
  price: "your_price_id",
  quantity: nights,
};

// Create a description for the line item
lineItem.description = `${nights} nights @ £${pricePerNight} a night`;

// Proceed with the rest of your code to call stripe.redirectToCheckout

stripe
  .redirectToCheckout({
    sessionId: session.id,
    lineItems: [lineItem],
  })
  .then(function (result) {
    // Handle the result
  });
```

This way, Stripe will display the line item description as '10 nights @ £50 a night'. If you cannot modify the description directly when creating the line item or session, you may consider adding this as additional product metadata when you create the product in Stripe. This metadata will then be visible in your Stripe dashboard but not displayed on the checkout page.

Unfortunately, for a complete control over the checkout page design, you would need to switch to Stripe Elements or a custom implementation that allows you to edit the template of the checkout page.

I apologize for the misunderstanding. You're correct that `description` is no longer a valid field for line items in the latest version of Stripe API.

In this case, since you are using the redirect to Checkout method, there is limited customization available for the checkout page. To display the desired custom text ('10 nights @ £50 a night'), you would need to adjust the name of the product that you're adding to the Stripe session.

Here's an example of how you can create a session with an adjusted product name:

```javascript
const stripe = require("stripe")("your_stripe_secret_key");

const nights = 10;
const pricePerNight = 50;

const session = await stripe.checkout.sessions.create({
  payment_method_types: ["card"],
  line_items: [
    {
      price_data: {
        currency: "gbp",
        product_data: {
          name: `${nights} nights @ £${pricePerNight} a night`, // Set the customized product name
        },
        unit_amount: pricePerNight * 100, // Convert to pence
      },
      quantity: nights,
    },
  ],
  mode: "payment",
  success_url: "https://yourdomain/success",
  cancel_url: "https://yourdomain/cancel",
});
```

Remember to replace `your_stripe_secret_key`, `yourdomain/success`, and `yourdomain/cancel` with your specific account details.

However, in this approach, you will need to make sure to handle stock and pricing management on your server since you're not using Stripe's pre-defined products or prices.

For a more customizable checkout experience, you may consider using Stripe Elements, which provide more control over the styling and contents of the checkout form. However, this also requires more work to implement, as you would need to handle the payment processing manually. You can learn more about Stripe Elements here: https://stripe.com/docs/stripe-js#elements

To create a payment with Stripe.redirectToCheckout that doesn't charge the customer immediately, you can use the `payment_intent_data.capture_method` parameter and set it to `manual`. This creates a PaymentIntent with the `requires_capture` state, allowing an admin to confirm the payment later.

Here's an example of how to create a session with the 'manual' capture method:

```javascript
const stripe = require("stripe")("your_stripe_secret_key");

const nights = 10;
const pricePerNight = 50;

const session = await stripe.checkout.sessions.create({
  payment_method_types: ["card"],
  line_items: [
    {
      price_data: {
        currency: "gbp",
        product_data: {
          name: `${nights} nights @ £${pricePerNight} a night`,
        },
        unit_amount: pricePerNight * 100, // Convert to pence
      },
      quantity: nights,
    },
  ],
  payment_intent_data: {
    capture_method: "manual", // Set capture_method to 'manual' to not charge the customer immediately
  },
  mode: "payment",
  success_url: "https://yourdomain/success?session_id={CHECKOUT_SESSION_ID}",
  cancel_url: "https://yourdomain/cancel",
});
```

After the customer submits their payment details, Stripe will authorize the payment, but it won't charge the customer's card. To confirm and capture the payment manually, an admin can use the Stripe Dashboard or you can implement a system on your backend to capture the payment using the Stripe API:

```javascript
const stripe = require('stripe')('your_stripe_secret_key');

// Replace 'your_payment_intent_id' with the payment intent ID received from the webhook or the Checkout session
const paymentIntent = await stripe.paymentIntents.capture('your_payment_intent_id');
```

Remember, you must capture the payment within seven days, or the authorization will expire and the funds will be released to the customer.

To store the PaymentIntent in your backend/database and capture it later, you should listen for the 'checkout.session.completed' event using Stripe webhooks. When the webhook is triggered, you can store the PaymentIntent ID in your database and confirm/capture it later.

Here's an example of how you can implement this using Node.js and Express:

1. First, configure your webhook endpoint in your Stripe Dashboard (https://dashboard.stripe.com/test/webhooks) to listen for the 'checkout.session.completed' event.

2. Next, implement the webhook handler in your server-side code (assuming you're using Express):

```javascript
const express = require("express");
const app = express();
const stripe = require("stripe")("your_stripe_secret_key");
app.use(express.json());

app.post("/webhook", async (req, res) => {
  const sig = req.headers["stripe-signature"];
  const endpointSecret = "your_webhook_signing_key";

  let event;

  try {
    event = stripe.webhooks.constructEvent(req.body, sig, endpointSecret);
  } catch (err) {
    res.status(400).send(`Webhook Error: ${err.message}`);
    return;
  }

  if (event.type === "checkout.session.completed") {
    const session = event.data.object;
    const paymentIntentId = session.payment_intent;

    // Store the PaymentIntent ID in your database
    // Replace this with your method to store the ID in your database
    storePaymentIntentIdInDatabase(paymentIntentId);
  }

  res.json({ received: true });
});

app.listen(8000, () => console.log("Listening on port 8000"));

async function storePaymentIntentIdInDatabase(paymentIntentId) {
  // Your logic to store the PaymentIntent ID in your database
}
```

3. After storing the PaymentIntent ID, you can query your database to retrieve the ID when you want to confirm/capture the payment. Then, you can use the Stripe API to capture the payment as shown below:

```javascript
const stripe = require("stripe")("your_stripe_secret_key");

// Replace 'your_payment_intent_id' with the PaymentIntent ID from your database
const paymentIntent = await stripe.paymentIntents.capture("your_payment_intent_id");
```

4. Finally, you can set up an interface in your admin dashboard where an admin can confirm payments, triggering the capture process.

Remember to replace 'your_stripe_secret_key', 'your_webhook_signing_key', and the 'storePaymentIntentIdInDatabase' function with your account details and database logic, respectively.

To implement this in a NestJS application, you can create a new module and controller for handling the webhook. Here's an example of how you can create and configure a Stripe webhook in a NestJS app.

1. Start by installing the Stripe package if you haven't already:

```sh
npm install stripe
```

2. Create a new module and controller using the NestJS CLI:

```sh
nest generate module stripe-webhook
nest generate controller stripe-webhook
```

3. In the `stripe-webhook.module.ts`, import and configure the necessary packages:

```typescript
import { Module } from '@nestjs/common';
import { StripeWebhookController } from './stripe-webhook.controller';

@Module({
  controllers: [StripeWebhookController],
})
export class StripeWebhookModule {}
```

4. Modify the `stripe-webhook.controller.ts` to handle the webhook events:

```typescript
import { Controller, Post, Req, Res } from '@nestjs/common';
import { Request, Response } from 'express';
import Stripe from 'stripe';

const stripe = new Stripe('your_stripe_secret_key', { apiVersion: '2020-08-27' });

@Controller('stripe-webhook')
export class StripeWebhookController {
  // Replace 'your_webhook_signing_key' with the signing key from your Stripe Dashboard
  private endpointSecret = 'your_webhook_signing_key';

  @Post()
  async handleStripeWebhook(@Req() req: Request, @Res() res: Response) {
    const sig = req.headers['stripe-signature'];
    let event;

    try {
      event = stripe.webhooks.constructEvent(req.body, sig, this.endpointSecret);
    } catch (err) {
      res.status(400).send(`Webhook Error: ${err.message}`);
      return;
    }

    if (event.type === 'checkout.session.completed') {
      const session = event.data.object;
      const paymentIntentId = session.payment_intent;

      // Store the PaymentIntent ID in your database
      await this.storePaymentIntentIdInDatabase(paymentIntentId);
    }

    return res.json({ received: true });
  }

  async storePaymentIntentIdInDatabase(paymentIntentId: string) {
    // Your logic to store the PaymentIntent ID in your database
  }
}
```

5. Update your `app.module.ts` file to import the new StripeWebhookModule:

```typescript
import { Module } from '@nestjs/common';
import { AppController } from './app.controller';
import { AppService } from './app.service';
import { StripeWebhookModule } from './stripe-webhook/stripe-webhook.module';

@Module({
  imports: [StripeWebhookModule],
  controllers: [AppController],
  providers: [AppService],
})
export class AppModule {}
```

6. In your `main.ts`, enable handling of raw buffers by adding `json({verify: ...})` as the Express middleware:

```typescript
import { NestFactory } from '@nestjs/core';
import { AppModule } from './app.module';
import { json } from 'express';

async function bootstrap() {
  const app = await NestFactory.create(AppModule);
  app.use(json({ verify: (req, _, buf) => (req['rawBody'] = buf) }));
  await app.listen(3000);
}
bootstrap();
```

7. Connect the webhook to the '/stripe-webhook' endpoint in your [Stripe Dashboard](https://dashboard.stripe.com/test/webhooks) and don't forget to replace `'your_stripe_secret_key'` and `'your_webhook_signing_key'` with your own keys.

